\begin_layout Title
Camera Trap Study on Farm Woltemade, Namibia: Did an increase in leopard
 numbers coincide with a decrease in cheetah numbers?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Chavoux Luyt
\end_layout

\begin_layout Part
Introduction 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
In addition to prey and habitat preferences, interaction with other predators
 is the third ecological aspect of predator behaviour that can determine
 management options for farmers.
 Especially for cheetahs, competition with larger predators is one of the
 main reasons why conserved areas are insufficient to ensure their long-term
 survival.
 A number of Namibian farmers have reported an increase in leopard numbers
 and a simultaneous decrease in cheetah numbers (pers.
 comm.
 Francois Kok, Rolf Ritter and others).
 The reported increase in leopards could be causing a decline in cheetah
 as the result of direct lethal confrontation between leopards and cheetahs,
 cheetahs avoiding areas with high leopard density ("fear and loathing"
 sensu 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Ritchie_and_Johnson_2009"

\end_inset

), habitat changes more favourable to leopards, changes in available prey
 species, a disproportionate number of cheetahs killed by farmers compared
 to leopards, or other currently unknown reasons.
 However, no such change has been reported on the land of the Cheetah Conservati
on Fund (CCF), where no predators are killed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Woltemade Guest and Hunting Farm is situated in North Central Namibia, about
 40km Northwest of Hochfeld 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Figure 1 Map of study site with camera trap stations"

\end_inset

.
 It is a guest and hunting farm as well as a working cattle farm of about
 22 000 ha with its own butchery in total and forms part of the Sandveld
 conservancy.
 The farm falls within the Thornbush shrubland vegetation type of Namibia,
 growing on chromic Cambisols in the southern part, petric Calcisols in
 the centre and ferric Arenosols soil types in the northern part of the
 farm.
 In 2008 CCF did a three month camera trap survey on the land, primarily
 to determine cheetah numbers.
 A total of 3890 pictures were taken, of which 19% where cheetahs, allowing
 for the identification of six different cheetahs 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Marker_2008"

\end_inset

.
 Other predators, including leopard, were also recorded.
 Two cameras were used per site and cameras were placed at 10 play trees
 and next to one road.
 This data presents us with an opportunity to test whether the perceived
 increase in leopard numbers really coincided with a decrease in cheetah
 numbers.
