\begin_layout Part
Aims and objectives 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
The main aim of the camera trap study is simply to determine if there has
 really been an increase in leopard numbers on the farm Woltemade and secondly,
 if such an increase coincided with a decrease in cheetah numbers.
 If such a change in numbers has indeed occurred, it would suggest that
 more research into the reasons for this change needs to be done to ensure
 the future survival of cheetahs on farmlands.
 Some circumstantial data will also be collected to suggest possible avenues
 of future research.
 There are a number of alternative hypotheses to be tested.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The null hypothesis (H0) is simply that there has been no significant change
 in either leopard or cheetah numbers.
 The perceived change that was reported might be simply because of an increase
 in livestock losses from leopard depredation, leading to farmers thinking
 that there has been an increase in leopard numbers.
 Increasing livestock losses from leopards might be caused by them switching
 to livestock as prey because of changes in wild prey availability, changes
 in farm management bringing more vulnerable livestock into contact with
 areas of high leopard density, or any number of other reasons that does
 not entail an increase in numbers.
 Because of the rise of conservancies, it is also possible that predators
 are less persecuted than before, changing their behaviour, and so they
 are simply seen more easily by farmers.
 Of course, since this study can only be done on the one farm for which
 historical data are available, it is also possible that the sample sizes
 might be too small to show significance (only four cheetah individuals
 identified during previous survey), even if there was a real change in
 numbers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
H1 There might be an actual increase in leopard numbers, but no change in
 cheetah numbers.
 This will indicate that a number of possible reasons could cause an increase
 in leopard numbers, but that these factors donâ€™t really influence the numbers
 of cheetahs and also that leopards are unlikely to influence cheetah numbers
 through direct competition or outright killing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
H2 There might both be an increase in the numbers of leopards and a simultaneous
 decrease in the numbers of cheetahs.
 While this will not indicate any reason for the changes in numbers, it
 would suggest that is possible that leopards can have a direct effect on
 the numbers of cheetahs and that this should be investigated further.
 Finding the reason for the changes will be important, both to ensure the
 long-term survival of the cheetah and for farmers to adapt their management
 practices to take into account the difference in behaviour and predation
 risk between leopards and cheetahs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
H3 There might be an increase in both leopard and cheetah numbers.
 This will indicate that circumstances have somehow changed (e.g.
 a change in habitat, number of available prey species or management changes)
 so that both predator species benefit.
 It might mean that farmers should consider additional management practices
 to protect their livestock from both predator species, but that the current
 management of Woltemade farm and neighbouring conservancy members are benefitin
g predator conservation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
H4 The last, very unlikely result, might be that there has actually been
 an increase in cheetah numbers, while leopard numbers decreased or stayed
 the same.
 This will be the opposite of what is being reported by most farmers and
 will also need more research to find the reason for such a change.
\end_layout

