\begin_layout Part
Conclusion 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Although the camera trap study will not be able to prove that there has
 been a general increase in leopard numbers (and simultaneous decrease in
 cheetah numbers) in Northern Namibia, it should be able to test if this
 effect as reported by one farmer, is real or not.
 Even if this data can not be extrapolated to the whole of North Central
 Namibia, it can provide supportive evidence that the reported change in
 predator composition on these farmlands are real.
 If there is a real effect, it will imply that more research is needed on
 the causes of the change in predator numbers.
 Any additional data on rainfall, vegetation changes, game and livestock
 numbers and management can also be provided as possible causes for the
 change in predator numbers that needs to be investigated.
 Spoor tracking will later (from July 2014 onward) be used to provide more
 detail on the spatial behaviour of the four predator species that can have
 an economic impact on livestock farming in Northern Namibia.
\end_layout

